citeinfo.origin: New Hampshire. Department of Environmental Services
citeinfo.othercit: Dr. Frederick Short, University of New Hampshire, Durham, NH

descript.abstract:
The dataset shows the locations where eelgrass was observed in the Great Bay Estuary based on low-altitude aerial surveillance in 1995. The study area includes the following waterbodies: Great Bay, the mouth of the Squamscott River, the tidal portion of the Lamprey River, the tidal portion of the Oyster River, the tidal portion of the Bellamy River, the Piscataqua River and Portsmouth Harbor and its associated creeks. Aerial photographs are taken of the study area at 3000 feet at low spring tide with roughly 60% overlap on a calm day without preceding rain events and when the sun is at a low angle to minimize reflection (between 7 am and 10 am). Photographs are taken in late summer, usually late August or early September, depending on tides and weather, to reflect the maximum eelgrass annual biomass. 35 mm film (ASA 200) or a digital camera is used to acquire the images. Typically 300 images are needed to cover the entire Great Bay Estuary. The orientation of the photographs is near-vertical. This is a slight deviation from the NOAA Coastal Change Analysis Program protocol, but follows a published method (Short and Burdick, 1986). The photographs, in the form of 35mm slides or digital computer images, are projected on a screen and the eelgrass images are transferred to a base map. These maps are then digitized using GIS software. The eelgrass habitat mapped from the aerial imagery is verified using the ground truthing data by placing the ground-truthing locations onto the digital image using GIS software. Ground-truthing is done from a small boat during the same season as the photographs are taken. Ground-truth observations are made at low tide. Samples are collected with an eelgrass sampling hook. Positions are determined using GPS. The ground-truth surveys assess 10-20% of the eelgrass beds mapped in the estuary. The aerial survey is completed yearly. The first survey in the series was completed in 1986.
Note that yearly variations in collection methods exist. Following is a summary of methods that have been used.
descript.purpose: This dataset is intended for researchers, students, and policy makers for reference and mapping purposes, and may be used for basic applications such as viewing, querying, and map output production, or to provide a basemap to support graphical overlays and analysis with other spatial data.

Ground-truthing is done from a small boat during the same season as the photographs are taken. Ground-truth observations are made at low tide. Samples are collected with an eelgrass sampling hook. Positions are determined using GPS. The ground-truth surveys assess 10-20% of the eelgrass beds mapped in the estuary. Overlapping polygon areas are identified and removed using a topology rule.

procstep.procdesc: The photographs, in the form of 35mm slides or digital computer images, are projected on a screen and the eelgrass images are transferred to a base map by hand (i.e., the polygons are hand-drawn on a hardcopy map of the estuary). The polygons on the hardcopy maps are later digitized.

procstep.procdesc:
The file name of this dataset was changed from Eelgrass1995 to NHEelgrass95.
This shapefile metadata was edited for clarity and keywords were added per Tufts metadata standards.

attracc.attraccr: Attribute information remains the same as given by the author of the data. However, when information is missing or ambiguous, the GIS Information Systems Center at Tufts University researches other metadata sources for explanations. If sufficient information is unavailable, "unknown attribute" is given as the definition. If the attribute has been created through a geoprocessing function, "geoprocessed identifier" is given. If the attribute is known, but the values are not, "unknown" is given for values. Features' units of measurement are determined if not already given.

enttyp.enttypd: Each polygon of eelgrass habitat is assigned an attribute in the density field of the attribute table. The values in the density field are qualitative assessments of the eelgrass density in each polygon.
enttyp.enttypds: New Hampshire. Department of Environmental Services

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: Area of the eelgrass in square feet.
Perimeter of the eelgrass area in feet.
Qualitative assessments of the eelgrass density in each polygon

edom.edomvd: Dense. Eelgrass covers 90-100% of the bottom. The bottom is not visible in the aerial photos. The shoot density or biomass level for eelgrass of this density is approximately 250 grams per square meter.

Some bottom. Eelgrass covers 60-90% of the bottom. Some bottom is visible in the aerial photos but the majority is covered by eelgrass. The shoot density or biomass level for eelgrass of this density is approximately 85 grams per square meter.

Half. Eelgrass covers 30-60% of the bottom. Approximately half the bottom is visible in the aerial photos. The shoot density or biomass level for eelgrass of this density is approximately 55 grams per square meter.

Partial. Eelgrass covers 10-30% of the bottom. Eelgrass is present but the majority of the bottom is still visible in the bed. The shoot density or biomass level for eelgrass of this density is approximately 25 grams per square meter.
Present. Eelgrass is present but the density could not be determined.
Present. Eelgrass is present but the density could not be determined.

Ruppia. Ruppia maritima is a different species of submerged aquatic vegetation than the Zostera marina that is mapped for this program. Ruppia can be found in the Great Bay Estuary at low levels, particularly in association with salt marsh pannes and in the upper reaches of the estuary. Ruppia was mapped if it appeared in large beds in parts of the tributaries where eelgrass could be expected.
No eelgrass. Polygon represents an island or area without eelgrass.
